<subSubSection id="88916555ED4D7D69B68EF8FACE2B783B" pageId="16" pageNumber="97" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="C03436DEED4D7D69B68EF8FACE2B783B" blockId="16.[704,1313,1712,2138]" pageId="16" pageNumber="97">
Widely used subspecific names caucasicus and zaisanicus have been changed for gender agreement. Based on DNA analysis, J. Pisano and colleagues in 2015 demonstrated that S. 
<taxonomicName id="078B4D5DED4D7D69B7E7F815C8C377D3" authorityName="Lichtenstein" authorityYear="1823" box="[934,1002,1992,2021]" class="Mammalia" family="Dipodidae" genus="Dipus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="16" pageNumber="97" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="telum">telum</taxonomicName>
and S. 
<taxonomicName id="078B4D5DED4D7D69B01FF815CFFB77D3" authorityName="Sokolov &amp; Shenbrot" authorityYear="1987" box="[1118,1234,1992,2021]" class="Mammalia" family="Dipodidae" genus="Stylodipus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Rodentia" pageId="16" pageNumber="97" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="sungorus">sungorus</taxonomicName>
were sister species. Six subspecies recognized.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
